A shiny compact disc sits in a vintage CD player tray, but from beneath the disc's reflective surface, dark mechanical tendrils and sinister robotic insect-like creatures crawl outward, burrowing into the circuitry of the device. The scene is rendered in a 1950s vintage advertising illustration style with muted teal, rust orange, and cream colors. The CD appears innocent and pristine on top while underneath reveals a hidden infestation of tiny clockwork parasites with glowing amber eyes, spreading like a disease through copper wires and vacuum tubes. The composition suggests betrayal—something trusted harboring something malicious. Dramatic shadows and halftone dot patterns typical of mid-century print ads give the image a retro propaganda poster quality, emphasizing the sinister nature lurking within everyday consumer electronics.
